[[File:Philippine National Police boat in Iloilo River.JPG|thumbnail|A boat belonging to the [[Philippine National Police]] at the [[Iloilo River]] in [[Iloilo City]]]] '''Crime''' is present in various forms in [[the Philippines]], and remains a serious issue throughout the country. [[Illegal drug trade]], [[human trafficking]], [[murder]], [[corruption]] and [[domestic violence]] remain significant concerns. The Philippines has a high rate of murder cases, which is the highest in [[Southeast Asia]] as of 2014. Most major cities are plagued with high prevalence of crimes.
== Crime by type ==
===Organized crime=== Organized crime in the Philippines can be linked to certain families or barkadas (groups) who perpetrate crimes ranging from [[extortion]], sale of illegal narcotics and [[loan sharking]] to [[robbery]], [[kidnapping]], and [[contract killing|murder-for-hire]].<ref>{{Cite web|author=Kowalzki, Eugene|date=12 July 2010|title=Filipino Gangs in the Philippines|publisher=Zimbio|url=http://www.zimbio.com/The+Philippines/articles/PR2SNUkbmGf/Filipino+Gangs+Philippines|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714163338/http://www.zimbio.com/The%2BPhilippines/articles/PR2SNUkbmGf/Filipino%2BGangs%2BPhilippines|archivedate=14 July 2010|deadurl=no|df=}}</ref> ====Illegal drug trade==== {{main|Illegal drug trade in the Philippines}} [[Illegal drug trade]] is common all around the Philippines, and is a major concern. [[Methamphetamine]] ("shabu") and [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] ("weeds" or "damo"), are the most common drugs accounting most drug-related arrests. Most of the illegal drug trade involved members of large [[Chinese people|Chinese]] [[Triad (organized crime)|triad groups]] operating in the Philippines, owing to its location on drug smuggling routes.
===Petty crime=== Petty crime, which includes pick-pocketing, is a problem in the Philippines. It takes place usually in locations with many people, ranging from shopping hubs to churches. Traveling alone to withdraw cash after dark is a risk, especially for foreigners.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://safety.worldnomads.com/Philippines/73433/Crime-in-the-Philippines |title=Crime in the Philippines |publisher=World Nomads |date=June 9, 2010 |accessdate=June 12, 2013 }}</ref>
=== Violent crime === {{See|Violence against women in the Philippines}} Violent crime is high in the country; foreigners are usually the victims. As many Filipinos are stricken with poverty, one alternative they take is to kidnap others for money.<ref name="auto"/> ====Rape==== {{main|Rape in the Philippines}} ====Murder==== In 2014, the Philippines has a murder rate of 9.84 per 100,000 people, with a number of 9,784 recorded cases. The country also has the highest rate of murder cases in Southeast Asia in 2013, with a rate of 8.8, followed by Thailand.{{sfn|UNODC|2014|p=24}} The murder rate in the Philippines reached its peak in 2002 and 2010, with rates of 8.1 (6,553 cases) and 9.5 (8,894 cases). {{Sfn|UNODC|2014|p=128}}
===Human trafficking=== {{Main|Human trafficking in the Philippines}} [[Human trafficking]] and the [[prostitution of children]] is a significant issue in the Philippines, often controlled by organized crime syndicates.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6507495.stm |date=1 April 2007 |title='Chairman' reveals seedy world of trafficking |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=2007-11-25 |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> Human trafficking in the country is a crime against humanity.<ref name="unodc.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/human-trafficking/what-is-human-trafficking.html|title=What is Human Trafficking?|publisher=|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="childtrafficking.org">[http://www.childtrafficking.org/cgi-bin/ct/main.sql?file=view_document.sql&TITLE=-1&AUTHOR=-1&THESAURO=-1&ORGANIZATION=-1&TOPIC=-1&GEOG=-1&YEAR=-1&LISTA=No&COUNTRY=-1&FULL_DETAIL=Yes&ID=2312 Child Trafficking<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.preventgenocide.org/law/icc/statute/part-a.htm#2|title=Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court (Articles 1 to 33)- Prevent Genocide International|publisher=|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=japan2.usembassy.gov>{{cite web|last=Hansen |first=Scott |title=Japan's Fight against Modern-Day Slavery (Part I) |url=http://japan2.usembassy.gov/e/p/tp-20080123-03.html |accessdate=11 June 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308152916/http://japan2.usembassy.gov/e/p/tp-20080123-03.html |archivedate=8 March 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name="globalnation.inquirer.net">{{cite web|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20091021-231421/Cebu-a--transit-point-for-child-trafficking |title=Cebu a transit point for child trafficking - INQUIRER.net, Philippine News for Filipinos |publisher= |accessdate=15 March 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327091536/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20091021-231421/Cebu-a--transit-point-for-child-trafficking |archivedate=27 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>
In an effort to deal with the problem, the Philippines passed Republic Act (R.A.) 9208, the [[Anti-Trafficking in Persons Act of 2003]], a penal law against [[human trafficking]], [[sex tourism]], [[sex slavery]] and [[Prostitution of children|child prostitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/republicactno9208.html|title=REPUBLIC ACT NO. 9208 - AN ACT TO INSTITUTE POLICIES TO ELIMINATE TRAFFICKING IN PERSONS ESPECIALLY WOMEN AND CHILDREN, ESTABLISHING THE NECESSARY INSTITUTIONAL MECHANISMS FOR THE PROTECTION AND SUPPORT OF TRAFFICKED PERSONS, PROVIDING PENALTIES FOR ITS VIOLATIONS, AND FOR OTHER|author=RONALD ECHALAS DIAZ, Office Manager|publisher=|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref> Nevertheless, enforcement is reported to be inconsistent.<ref name="IrishRevealed">{{cite web|title=Revealed: In Cities and Towns All Over the Philippines, Irishmen Pay to Have Sex with Children|url=http://www.tribune.ie/article.tvt?_scope=TribuneFTF&id=77709|date=2006-09-24|work=[[The Sunday Tribune]]|publisher=Tribune Newspapers PLC|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5OzhDYYFa?url=http://www.tribune.ie/article.tvt?_scope=TribuneFTF&id=77709|archivedate=2007-05-21|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> ====Prostitution==== {{Main|Prostitution in the Philippines}} [[Prostitution in the Philippines]] is illegal. It is a serious crime with penalties ranging up to [[life imprisonment]] for those involved in [[Human trafficking|trafficking]]. It is covered by the Anti-Trafficking in Persons Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/republicactno9208.html|title=REPUBLIC ACT NO. 9208 - AN ACT TO INSTITUTE POLICIES TO ELIMINATE TRAFFICKING IN PERSONS ESPECIALLY WOMEN AND CHILDREN, ESTABLISHING THE NECESSARY INSTITUTIONAL MECHANISMS FOR THE PROTECTION AND SUPPORT OF TRAFFICKED PERSONS, PROVIDING PENALTIES FOR ITS VIOLATIONS, AND FOR OTHER|author=RONALD ECHALAS DIAZ, Office Manager|publisher=|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref> [[prostitution]] is still sometimes illegally available through [[brothels]] (also known as ''casa''), bars, [[karaoke bar]]s, [[massage parlor]]s, street walkers and [[escort service]]s.<ref name="Havoscope 1"/> {{as of|2009}}, one source estimates that there are 800,000 women working as prostitutes in the Philippines, with some of them believed to be underage.<ref name="Havoscope 1">{{cite web |url = http://www.havocscope.com/number-of-prostitutes-in-the-philippines/| title= Number of prostitutes in the Philippines |publisher=Havoscope |accessdate=June 12, 2013 }}</ref> While victims are largely female, and according to the current Revised Penal Code, there are in fact a small minority of them who are male.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pcw.gov.ph/anti-prostitution-bill |title=Anti-Prostitution Bill |publisher=Philippine Commission on Women |accessdate=June 12, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707085350/http://pcw.gov.ph/anti-prostitution-bill |archivedate=July 7, 2013 |df= }}</ref>
===Corruption and police misconduct=== {{Main|Corruption in the Philippines}}
Corruption is a great problem in the Philippines. In May 2013, during the country's elections, some 504 political candidates were accused mostly of corruption and some of violent crimes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pcij.org/stories/sandiganbayan-files-256-poll-winners-have-graft-crime-cases-17-convicted/ |title=Sandiganbayan files: 256 poll winners have graft, crime cases; 17 convicted |newspaper=The Philippines Centre of Investigative Journalism |date=June 10, 2013 }}</ref> Police misconduct is a known issue in the country; in April 2013, a short video, titled ''Like a BOSS'', showcasing the assault on an unarmed individual by three police officers went viral online, prompting the [[Philippine National Police]] to investigate the matter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philstar.com/nation/2013/04/08/928358/pnp-probes-brutality-viral-video |title=PNP probes 'brutality' in viral video |date=April 8, 2013 |last=Diola |first=Camille |newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]] }}</ref>
