Before {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/i, e, ɛ/}} are rounded to {{IPA|[ʏ, ø, œ]}}.

In southern varieties of Northern Bavarian the diphthongs {{IPA|/iə̯, uə̯/}} are realized with an opener offset, i.e. {{IPA|[iɐ̯, uɐ̯]}}.

An interesting aspect of the diphthongs are the so-called ''reversed diphthongs'', or in German, ''gestürzte Diphthonge''. They are called so because the [[Middle High German]] diphthongs {{IPA|[ie̯, ye̯, uo̯]}} became {{IPA|[ei̯, ou̯]}} ({{IPA|[y]}} became {{IPA|[i]}} after unrounding) in Northern Bavarian, while they generally became {{IPA|[iː, yː, uː]}} in [[Standard German]]. Compare Standard German ''Brief'' {{IPA|[briːf]}}, ''Bruder'' {{IPA|[ˈbruːdɐ]}}, ''Brüder'' {{IPA|[ˈbryːdɐ]}} and Northern Bavarian {{IPA|[ˈb̥rei̯v̥]}}, {{IPA|[ˈb̥rou̯d̥ɐ]}}, {{IPA|[ˈb̥rei̯d̥ɐ]}}.<ref>{{cite book | last = Renn | first = Manfred  | last2 = König | first2 = Werner | year = 2006 | title = Kleiner Bayerischer Sprachatlas | isbn = 3-423-03328-2 | pages = 62–64, 37 }}</ref>

The Northern Bavarian diphthong {{IPA|[ɔu̯]}} corresponds to the Middle High German and Standard German {{IPA|[oː, aː]}}. Compare Standard German ''Schaf'' {{IPA|[ʃaːf]}}, ''Stroh'' {{IPA|[ʃtroː]}} and Northern Bavarian {{IPA|[ʒ̊ɔu̯v̥]}}, {{IPA|[ʒ̊d̥rɔu̯]}}.<ref>{{cite book | last = Renn | first = Manfred  | last2 = König | first2 = Werner | year = 2006 | title = Kleiner Bayerischer Sprachatlas | isbn = 3-423-03328-2 | pages = 40–41, 44–45 }}</ref> Likewise, the Northern Bavarian diphthong {{IPA|[ɛi̯]}} corresponds to the Middle High German and Standard German {{IPA|[eː]}} and by unrounding to {{IPA|[øː]}}. Compare Standard German ''Schnee'' {{IPA|[ʃneː]}}, ''böse'' {{IPA|[ˈbøːzə]}} with Northern Bavarian {{IPA|[ʒ̊n̥ɛi̯]}}, {{IPA|[b̥ɛi̯z̥]}}.<ref>{{cite book | last = Renn | first = Manfred  | last2 = König | first2 = Werner | year = 2006 | title = Kleiner Bayerischer Sprachatlas | isbn = 3-423-03328-2 | pages = 46–47, 37 }}</ref>

In many Northern Bavarian variants, [[nasalization]] is increasingly common.

