== Grammar ==

=== Nouns ===

==== Gender ====
All [[noun]]s in Northern Bavarian one of have three [[Grammatical gender|genders]]: feminine, masculine and neuter. Many nouns have the same gender as in [[Standard German]], but there are many exceptions. An example is ''Benzin'', which is neuter in Standard German, but masculine in Northern Bavarian. Another example is ''Butter'', which is feminine in Standard German, but can be all three genders in Northern Bavarian depending on where in the Northern Bavarian–speaking you are.<ref>{{cite book | last = Zehetner | first = Ludwig | year = 1985 | title = Das bairische Dialektbuch | isbn = 3-406-30562-8 | pages = 121–123 }}</ref>

==== Case ====
As in Standard German there are four cases in Northern Bavarian: [[nominative]], [[accusative]], [[genitive]] and [[dative]]. The genitive case, however, is uncommon and is commonly replaced either with the dative and a [[possessive pronoun]] or with the [[preposition]] ''von'' {{IPA|[v̥ə, v̥ən, v̥əm]}} and the dative, e.g. {{IPA|[m̩̩ v̥ɑtɐ z̥ãi haːu̯z̥]}}, or {{IPA|[s̩ haːu̯z̥ v̥om v̥ɑtɐ]}} ''father's house''.  An exception is the genitive instead of the dative after the singular possessive pronouns, e.g. {{IPA|[hintɐ mai̯nɐ]}}, which is as correct as {{IPA|[hintɐ miɐ̯]}} ''behind me''. Prepositions take the dative or the accusative, but not the genitive, e.g. {{IPA|[d̥rots n̩ reːŋ]}} (formally {{IPA|[d̥rots m̩ reːŋ]}}) ''despite the rain''. The dative ending -m often sounds like the accusative ending -n (see the previous example), so that these two cases are not distinguishable.<ref>{{cite book | last = Zehetner | first = Ludwig | year = 1985 | title = Das bairische Dialektbuch | isbn = 3-406-30562-8 | pages = 106–108 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Merkle | first = Ludwig | year = 2005 | title = Bairische Grammatik | isbn = 3-86520-078-8 | pages = 96–99, 184–185 }}</ref>

==== Inflection ====
Nouns in Northern Bavarian are [[Inflection|inflected]] for number, and to a lesser extent, case. Inflecting for number is common across all three genders, and especially [[Germanic umlaut|umlaut]] is productive, in particular in masculine nouns. The most common plural marker in feminine nouns is {{IPA|[n]}}, while it is {{IPA|[ɐ]}} with most neuter nouns. Many nouns, across the genders, are the same in the [[plural]] as in the [[grammatical number|singular]].

:[[English language|English]] ''head'', Standard German ''Kopf'', Northern Bavarian sg. m. {{IPA|[kʰoːb̥͡v]}} > pl. {{IPA|[kʰep͡f]}}
:[[English language|English]] ''cat'', Standard German ''Katze'', Northern Bavarian sg. f. {{IPA|[kʰɑt͡s]}} > pl. {{IPA|[kʰɑt͡sn̩]}}
:[[English language|English]] ''house'', Standard German ''Haus'', Northern Bavarian sg. n. {{IPA|[haːu̯z̥]}} > pl. {{IPA|[haːi̯z̥ɐ]}}

Weak masculine nouns are inflected in the accusative and dative case, most commonly with [[suffixation]] of a nasal consonant, such as {{IPA|[m]}} or {{IPA|[n]}}, while the other cases remain uninflected. Many weak feminine nouns have the ending {{IPA|[n]}} in most cases, though not to be confused with the plural ending. Weak neuter nouns have almost been lost, with only strong remaining, and therefore inflection for case is basically nonexistent.

:[[English language|English]] ''boy'', Standard German ''Bube'', Northern Bavarian m. nom. {{IPA|[dɐ bou̯]}} > m. acc./dat. {{IPA|[n̩ bou̯m]}}

=== Adjectives ===
The [[inflection]] of [[adjective]]s in Northern Bavarian differ depending on whether the adjective is preceded by a [[definite article]] or a [[demonstrative]], or if it is preceded by an [[indefinite article]] or a [[possessive]], or if it is used as a [[Predicate (grammar)|predicate]], of which the latter is only present in some varieties. Adjectives without any [[determiner (linguistics)|determiner]] rarely occur.

Below can the inflectional paradigms be seen, with the adjective {{IPA|[ɔːld̥]}} serving as an example. This is also the form used in all situations, when the adjective is used as a predicate, and therefore no paradigm is needed. Compare Northern Bavarian {{IPA|[ɔːld̥]}} with the Standard German ''alt'', in [[English language|English]] ''old''.

