The predicate form of an adjective differ from the other forms, not only because it is the basic form, but also because it has a long vowel, unlike the other forms, as in {{IPA|[ɔːld̥]}} above. Other examples include {{IPA|[ɡ̊rɔːu̯z̥]}} and {{IPA|[b̥rɔːɐ̯d̥]}}, which become {{IPA|[ɡ̊rou̯s]}} and {{IPA|[b̥roi̯t]}}, respectively. Compare with the Standard German ''gross'' and ''breit'', in [[English language|English]] ''big'' and ''broad''.

Comparative adjectives are formed by suffixing {{IPA|[ɐ]}}, and superlative adjectives are formed by suffixing {{IPA|[st]}}. Vowel changes often take place when the suffixation happens. An example is {{IPA|[hɔːu̯ɣ̊]}}, which becomes {{IPA|[ˈhɛi̯xɐ]}} when comparative and {{IPA|[ˈhɛi̯kst]}} when superlative. Compare with the Standard German ''hoch'', ''höher'' and ''höchsten'', in English ''high'', ''higher'' and ''highest''.

