There is no gender distinction in the plural.

The ending {{IPA|[j]}} in the stressed first person singular nominative and -accusative and in stressed the second person singular accusative is only present in northern- and western varieties of Northern Bavarian.

At the time of a linguistic survey carried out in the late 1980s,<ref name="tdomg" /> pronouns also existed for unstressed first person plural accusative and unstressed second person plural accusative, {{IPA|[iz]}} and {{IPA|[iç]}}, respectively, but they have probably fallen out of usage today.

=== Verbs ===
[[Verb]]s in Northern Bavarian are [[Grammatical conjugation|conjugated]] for [[grammatical person|person]], [[grammatical tense|tense]] and [[grammatical mood|mood]]. The Northern Bavarian verbs are also subject to both vowel change and [[apophony]].

==== Non-finite forms ====
The [[non-finite verb|non-finite]] forms have one three endings: {{IPA|[∅]}}, {{IPA|[n]}} and {{IPA|[ɐ]}}. The first ending is rare, and is only present in some few monosyllabic verbs, such as {{IPA|[za͡i]}}, Standard German ''sein'', [[English language|English]] ''to be''; {{IPA|[ɡ̊ɛi]}}, Standard German ''gehen'', [[English language|English]] ''to go''; {{IPA|[ʒ̊d̥ɛi]}}, [[Standard German]] ''stehen'', [[English language|English]] ''to stand''; and {{IPA|[d̥o͡u]}}, Standard German ''tun'', [[English language|English]] ''to do''. The second ending is the most common ending found on most verbs, such as {{IPA|[b̥itn̩]}}, Standard German ''bitten'', [[English language|English]] ''to ask''. The third ending is used with verbs having a certain stem-final consonant, such as {{IPA|[z̥iŋɐ]}}, Standard German ''singen'', [[English language|English]] ''to sing''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Kranzmayer | first = E. | year = 1956 | title = Historische Lautgeographie des gesamtbairischen Dialektaumes}}</ref>

==== Present tense ====
The personal endings for the [[present tense]] differ slightly from variety to variety, but are largely uniform. The endings in the scheme below are attached to the stem, and not the non-finite form. The stem is found by removing the non-finite ending, if it is {{IPA|[n]}} or {{IPA|[ɐ]}}.

{| class="wikitable"
|- align=center
! rowspan="1" |
! [[Grammatical number|Singular]]
! [[Plural]]
|- align=center
! [[Grammatical person|First person]]
| -Ø
| ''nf.''
|- align=center
! [[Grammatical person|Second person]]
| -{{IPA|[z̥d̥]}}
| -{{IPA|[t͡s]}}
|- align=center
! [[grammatical person|Third person]]
| -{{IPA|[d̥]}}
| ''nf.''
|}

As can be seen in the scheme above, the first person singular is basically the same as the stem, and the first- and third persons plural are the same as the non-finite form. Furthermore, the third person singular is realized as -{{IPA|[d̥]}} when occurring before a fortis obstruent, and that in some southern varieties of Northern Bavarian the first person plural has the ending -{{IPA|[mɐ]}}, and therefore isn't the non-finite form.

The singular imperative is the same as the first person singular, and the plural imperative is the same as the second person plural. Only one exception exists, which is the imperative of {{IPA|[z̥a͡i]}}, Standard German ''sein'', [[English language|English]] ''to be'', which is {{IPA|[b̥iː]}}.

==== Past tense ====
Only one verb with a distinct [[simple past|simple past tense]] form remains, {{IPA|[z̥ai̯]}}, Standard German ''sein'', [[English language|English]] ''to be'', with the simple past tense form {{IPA|[βoə̯]}}, Standard German ''war'', [[English language|English]] ''was''. The [[past tense]] of other verbs is formed in the same way as Standard German uses ''haben'' or ''sein'', [[English language|English]] ''to have'' and ''to be'', respectively, and the [[past participle]].

The past participle in Northern Bavarian is formed by the [[prefix]] {{IPA|[ɡ̊]}}-, although not on verbs beginning with a [[plosive consonant]], where the prefix is left out. Thus we see {{IPA|[ɡ̊ʒ̊it]}}, Standard German ''geschüttet'', [[English language|English]] ''shaken''; {{IPA|[ɡ̊numɐ]}}, Standard German ''genommen'', [[English language|English]] ''taken''; {{IPA|[b̥rɑxd̥]}}, Standard German ''gebracht'', [[English language|English]] ''brought''; and {{IPA|[d̥roŋ]}}, Standard German ''getragen'', [[English language|English]] ''carried''.

The verbs {{IPA|[hɔm]}} and {{IPA|[z̥ai̯]}}, Standard German ''haben'' and ''sein'', [[English language|English]] ''to have'' and ''to be'', can be seen conjugated in the scheme below in the present, as they are [[irregular verb|irregular]]. They have the past participles, {{IPA|[ɡ̊hɔt]}} and {{IPA|[ɡ̊βeːn]}}, respectively. Compare with Standard German ''gehaben'' and ''gewesen'', [[English language|English]] ''had'' and ''been''.

