Examples can be seen below:
* {{IPA|[iː hoː ɡ̊ʒ̊it]}}, Standard German ''Ich habe geschüttet'', [[English language|English]] ''I have shaken''
* {{IPA|[eɐ̯ hɔu̯d̥ b̥rɑxd̥]}}, Standard German ''Er hat gebracht'', [[English language|English]] ''He has brought''

==== Subjunctive ====
It is quite straightforward to form the [[subjunctive]] in Northern Bavarian. The subjunctive of verbs is formed with the suffix -{{IPA|[ɐd̥]}}, as in {{IPA|[βisn̩]}} > {{IPA|[βisɐd̥]}}, Standard German ''wissen'' > ''wüßte'', [[English language|English]] ''to know'' > ''I would know''.

==== Apophony ====
Both [[Germanic weak verb|weak verb]]s and [[Germanic strong verb|strong verb]]s may undergo [[apophony]]. The strong verbs can be split into two groups: the first group where the vowel in the non-finite form is the same as in the past participle; and the second group where the vowel in the non-finite form is different from the vowel in the past participle. The most common vowel gradations in the second group can be seen below:

* {{IPA|[ai̯]}} > {{IPA|[i(ː)]}}: {{IPA|[ʒ̊nai̯n]}} > {{IPA|[ɡ̊ʒ̊niːn]}}, Standard German ''schneiden'' > ''geschnitten'' - [[English language|English]] ''to cut''
* {{IPA|[ei̯]}} > {{IPA|[o]}}, {{IPA|[uɐ̯]}}: {{IPA|[b̥ei̯n]}} > {{IPA|[b̥uɐ̯n]}}, Standard German ''bieten'' > ''geboten'' - [[English language|English]] ''to offer''
* {{IPA|[i]}} > {{IPA|[u]}}: {{IPA|[ziŋɐ]}} > {{IPA|[ɡ̊z̥uŋɐ]}}, Standard German ''singen'' > ''gesungen'' - [[English language|English]] ''to sing''
* {{IPA|[ɛ]}} > {{IPA|[o]}}: {{IPA|[d̥rɛʃn̩]}} > {{IPA|[d̥roʃn̩]}}, Standard German ''dreschen'' > ''gedroschen'' - [[English language|English]] ''to thresh''

Apophony is not as common with weak verbs as in Standard German. However, the number of weak verbs with [[morphophonology|morphophonological]] variations is high, especially change in [[vowel length]] is common.

