The '''Reprisal Generation''' is the name given by [[sociology|sociologists]] to describe the [[generation]] of people, born 1512–1540. It is an identified cohort within the [[Strauss–Howe generational theory]].<ref>[[Neil Howe]], [[William Strauss]], [[Generations (book)|Generations]]: The [[American history|History of America]]'s Future, 1584 to 2069 ([[Harper Collins]], 1992).</ref>
''”They spent their [[childhood]] amid religious frenzy and a widespread erosion of social authority—and came of age in a cynical, post-Awakening era of cut-throat politics and roller-coaster markets.''”<ref>William Strauss, The Fourth Turning: An American Prophecy - What the Cycles of History Tell Us About America's Next Rendezvous with Destiny (Doubleday, 1997). P127</ref> They crewed the ships during the wars of the [[Spanish Armada]] and saw the expansion of British territories and [[Colonial America|colonisation]] in the [[New World]] overseas.<ref>Neil Howe, Millennials Rising: The Next Great Generation (2000).</ref> <ref>Howe, Neil; Strauss, William, The Fourth Turning. (Broadway Books, 1997).</ref>
==Notable people== [[Elizabeth I]], [[Catherine de Medici]], [[Francis Drake]], [[John Hawkins (naval commander)|John Hawkins]], [[Thomas Gresham]], [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley]], [[Francis Walsingham]], [[Michel de Montaigne]], [[Walter Raleigh]], [[Nicholas Fuller (lawyer)|Nicholas Fuller]], and [[Edward Coke]].
